title: For Trade:  Canick TP-9 9mm
postcontent:
I have for trade a Cannik TP-9 9mm in Desert Tan. These are made in Turkey and imported to the U.S.
Pistol is a clone/improvement over the Smith and wesson/Walther p99 9mm. 
Pistol has seen approximately 50 rounds. Bought for personal carry but am getting into cowboy action shooting...so some of my handguns need to go.
Pistol comes in factory with case with all factory accessories. 
Includes: 
 Pistol 9mm 
1) 2 17 round magazines
2) Magazine loader
3) Cleaning brush and patch pull-through rod (made of vinyl)
4) Holster with belt clip and paddle clip (paddle installed on holster)
5) second backstrap for bigger hands
6) 3 front sights these are different heights to adjust for aim, plus sight removal/install tools.
7) lock and key
8) Padded, form fit case.
Pistol has a decocker on top of slide that works well and has a 2 stage trigger that removes the creep and slack of most striker fired pistols. The striker has a red rear face that protrudes from the slide to show it is cocked. This is one of the only true double action striker pistols i have found. The first stage of the trigger removes the slack. Once pulled to that point it catches on the second stage, the second stage has the typical slight creep but is a clean and predictable let off. Pistol recoils nicely and Has had no malfunctions being fed winchester white box and self defense ammo. 
Ive started playing cowboy on the weekends and am in need of boosting my six gun collection. will trade for cowboy action six gun. either cap and ball, a cap and ball converted to cartridge or single action 6. would truly love to trade for a Ruger old army or vaquero in 45lc/38spcl or an 1860 army converted to cartridge
To even things out in trade i have a Pietta 1851 confederate navy in brass that i can also toss in for the right deal or balance out a trade.
No cash price as i Dont have alot of money to buy a new vaquero or converted pistol. looking for used...

title: For Sale:  Lifted 2002 Z71 Avalanche
postcontent:
I came to the sad realization a short time ago that unless I want to start living in it; I can't afford to keep my truck AND go back to school as I plan to do. This means I'm forced to sell it; sad as it makes me. let me apologize in advance for the long ad, there's just a lot to know about the truck.

- 5.3 Liter LM7 engine, I'm a certified GM technician, I've seen these engines take some pretty serious abuse and come out begging for more

- Z71 off road suspension package

-Tow package

- M30 4 speed auto trans, with tow/haul mode

-Trailer brake module

- Power moon roof

-Fog lamps

- Automatic climate control with rear vents

-Power mirrors

- 4 inch lift kit

-G80 locking rear diff, previous owner had it rebuilt last year, I have invoice to prove it

- Brand new front wheel hub/bearings

- Electric 4 wheel drive selection, including automatic mode

- Power leather heated seats, with position memory for two drivers, this is seriously a luxury that you think of as silly until you have it and realize just how awesome it really is. 

-Kicker audio speakers, Sony MP3 loading stereo head, MP3 player goes inside and controlled through stereo head, previous owner had a sub-woofer in it but I didn't want it, all the cables are still there and ready to be hooked up. 

- CB/PA, needs antenna and speaker, previous owner installed, I never finished it, pretty neat though. 

-MB Chaos 5 wheels, 31" Goodyear Duratrac tires with moderate tread life left, I planned on running them at least another winter. They are a little noisy, but that's what you get with off road tires.

- Spectre performance air intake kit

-Running boards

The avalanche also features a folding rear wall which opens to bed into the cab, makes for a great sleeper if you camp and don't feel like putting up a tent. Two locking compartments on either side of the bed make great storage for things you want with you but don't want to shuffle around constantly, and are large enough to accommodate a decent sized rifle, or fishing rods, or whatever you want to put in them. 

All that said; it's tough, and it's nice, but it's not perfect. The exhaust tips are pretty haggard, I planned on replacing them but never got to it. Has a few blemishes in the paint, no major dents. The rear bumper is a little cock-eyed on the right side, previous owner says someone backed into it... I think he lightly tapped a stump, who knows. The bed isn't totally water tight, leaks just a little on the rear corners, but it's a lot dryer than an open bed. The On-star doesn't work, GM decommissioned all analog onstar systems awhile back. You can buy a digital conversion kit for it, but they're kinda spendy. It has keyless entry locks and an alarm, but the last remote I had broke and I didn't bother to replace it. Water pump just developed a slow leak I've noticed. 

All in all it's a fantastic truck and I've had a lot of fun with it. If I thought there was any way I could cut my hours back and keep this truck I would. But I can't. Text or call Stan at REDACTED for an opportunity to take a look and to go for a test drive. Pretty firm on price, credit union holds the title so I have to be able to pay them off. However I may be able to give some credit to a trade of the right Japanese wheeler. Thanks for reading, I look forward to hearing from you.

title: For Sale:  Hi-Point C9 w/ accessories
postcontent:
Like all Hi-Point products, the C9 is a semiautomatic single-stack, chambered for 9mm Luger and +P certified.  Previous owner bought it new and fired about a hundred rounds.  I never got the chance to fire this pistol myself.  Other than a little chamber-wear from its limited use, it's still in like-new condition.  The optional peephole sight has been installed, though the original rear sight (notch and two orange dots) is included if you'd prefer it, and can be installed with a the same small, flat-blade screwdriver you'd need to adjust the signts at all.  Personally, I'd stick with the peephole; at self-defense ranges, if any portion of your target, and any part of the forward sight's yellow stripe, are both within the circle, you're going to hit close enough.

One standard magazine (8 rounds) and one extended magazine (10 rounds) are included, cross-compatible with Hi-Point's .380ACP model.  Original case included, heavy-duty plastic, padding, and a (bought) keyed padlock that fits its holes.  Up to three holsters are also included.  One, really suited for a slightly smaller pistol, I bought from the FFL that handled the swap that got me this pistol in the first place, just because I needed it for a job the very next day (in Arizona, where being openly armed while helping a lady at the farmer's market had already prevented one robbery attempt).  The second holster, bought off of Hi-Point's website, fits much better and has a pouch for an extra magazine, fitting both standard and extended.  The third is only for concealed carry, as it looks like a black leather fanny-pack, and I'll only include that one if shown an up-to-date CCW permit by the buyer.

Sixty-odd rounds of reloaded 9mm FMJ will be included, enough to familiarize yourself with the pistol at the range, plus a few rounds of assorted hollow points, with enough name-brand +P's to fill either magazine and one in the chamber, but not both mags at once.  I generally carried it with the standard mag and 8+1 +P's, and ten FMJs in the extended in either the holster's ammo pouch or the fanny-pack's rear pocket.

Cash much preferred, as one of the things I'm selling this for is so I can get Oregon ID after my move, meaning check cashing is a bit problematic, at least 'til my freelance tech support business gets off the ground again.
